  "prompt": "How do doc2vec create vector of a document?",
  "response": "Doc2Vec is an extension of Word2Vec that is used to create vector representations for larger chunks of text, such as sentences, paragraphs, or entire documents. It was introduced by researchers at Google in a paper titled \"Distributed Representations of Sentences and Documents.\"\n\nDoc2Vec comes in two main variants: Distributed Memory (DM) and Distributed Bag of Words (DBOW). Here\u2019s a brief overview of how each variant works:\n\n### 1. Distributed Memory (DM)\nIn the DM model, the idea is to predict a target word using both the context words and a unique document vector that represents the entire document. The process involves:\n\n- **Context words**: These are words surrounding the target word within a specified window size.\n- **Document vector**: This is a fixed vector that represents the entire document and is trained alongside word vectors.\n\nThe DM model essentially works like an extension of the Continuous Bag of Words (CBOW) model from Word2Vec:\n- For each word in the document, a context window is defined.\n- The document vector (which is shared across all words in the document) and the context word vectors are concatenated or averaged.\n- This combined vector is used to predict the target word.\n- Both the context word vectors and the document vector are adjusted during training to minimize prediction error.\n\n### 2. Distributed Bag of Words (DBOW)\nThe DBOW model is somewhat simpler and resembles the Skip-Gram model from Word2Vec:\n- It ignores the context words.\n- Instead, it uses the document vector to predict the occurrence of words within the document.\n- The document vector is adjusted to improve the prediction accuracy of the words in the document.\n\nIn DBOW:\n- For each word in the document, the document vector is used to predict the word.\n- The document vector is trained to maximize the probability of predicting the correct words that appear in the document.\n\n### Training Process\nThe training process for both models typically involves stochastic gradient descent and backpropagation. During training, the vectors are continuously adjusted to minimize the error in word predictions. After training, the document vectors can be used in various machine learning tasks.\n\n### Summary\nTo summarize, Doc2Vec creates vector representations of documents by:\n- Associating each document with a unique vector.\n- Training these vectors along with word vectors to predict either context words (DM) or individual words (DBOW).\n- Adjusting the vectors during training to minimize prediction errors.\n\nThese document vectors capture semantic information about the document, allowing for tasks like document classification, clustering, similarity measurement, and more.",
